I have been using it in the following combination for a long time.

XMODIFIERS="@im=ibus" ; export XMODIFIERS
GTK_IM_MODULE="xim" ; export GTK_IM_MODULE

This is because the ibus that gtk tries to use directly interferes with the ibus and xim, causing something like chattering to occur.
However, upon investigating the input method module for gtk4, it seems that only /usr/local/lib/gtk-4.0/4.0.0/immodules/libim-ibus.so is installed.
It seems that for gtk4, GTK_IM_MODULE must have ibus set.

However, it seems that GTK_IM_MODULE allows for splitting by colon, so it appears that two modules can be configured.

Quote from gtk-4.18.4/gtk/gtkimmodule.c
  envvar = g_getenv ("GTK_IM_MODULE");
  if (envvar)
    {
      char **immodules;
      immodules = g_strsplit (envvar, ":", 0);
      context_id = lookup_immodule (display, immodules);
      g_strfreev (immodules);

So, would it be better if it was described that such a setting method exists?
